2.1 Data Input


1. Keyboard Input

Entering data directly into R using the keyboard. It is useful if:

  1. If the number of values is small, keyboard entry can be efficient.
  2. R has a number of functions for quickly generating patterned data.

For large amouts of data, however, keyboard entry is likely to be inefficient and error-prone.

x <- c(1, 2, 3, 4)
names <- c("John", "Sandy", "Mary")
v <- c(TRUE, FALSE)

You can create each column or each row by yourself, and then combine them as a data frame or list.

cooperation <- c(49, 64, 37, 52, 68, 54, 61, 79, 64, 29, 27, 58, 52, 41, 30,

cooperation
condition <- rep(c("public", "anonymous"), c(10, 10))

Guyer <- data.frame(cooperation, condition, sex)

cooperation <- scan()

3. read.table()


(1) reads a data frame

If you already set your work directory as ~/Documents, then you can access the data by type in its file name directly. javascript:;

# Data in Local File
Prestige <- read.table("~/Documents/Prestige.txt", header = TRUE)
Prestige <- read.table("Prestige.txt", header = TRUE)
# Data from the Internet
Prestige <- read.table("https://socialsciences.mcmaster.ca/jfox/Books/Companion/data/Prestige.txt", 
    header = TRUE)


(2) Errors in rows

Firstly, take a look of the file Prestige-bugged.txt,



There are errors when loading the data and the error message as follows. Then we have to find out the rows without 7 elements.

Prestige <- read.table("Prestige-bugged.txt", header = TRUE)
> Error in scan(file = file, what = what, sep = sep, quote = quote, dec = dec, : line 34 did not have 7 elements

Use count.fields() to detect the counts of elements in each row.

file <- "Prestige-bugged.txt"
counts <- count.fields(file)
counts
>   [1] 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 6
>  [36] 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 6 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 6 7 7 7 6 7 7
>  [71] 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7
which(counts != 7)  # print the index of counts not equal to 7
> [1] 35 54 64 68

Then we can fix the rows with problems.


(3) some additional arguments

  • colClasses - specify column modes (e.g. colClasses = c('character', 'character', 'integer', 'integer'))
  • col.names - specify column names, similar in spirit to names() (specify the names of each column if your original dataset doesnt specify them)
  • row.names - specify row names
  • sep - specify the delimiter, default: white space
  • skip - number of lines to skip before reading
  • na.strings - how missing values are recorded


4. read.fwf()

Use read.fwf() to import data when you want to specify the amount of words of each column. Take a look of the file Prestige-fixed.txt.



There are no white spaces or any kind of delimiter between each points, and there are no column names and row names. Then we specify ourselves.

Prestige <- read.fwf("Prestige-fixed.txt", col.names = c("occupation", "education", 
    "income", "women", "prestige", "census", "type"), row.names = "occupation", 
    widths = c(25, 5, 5, 5, 4, 4, 4))

2.2 Working with Data Frames

2.2.2 Avoiding attach()

Use the dataset Duncan.txt used in chapter 1, as we mentioned before, we can access the columns in the dataset by following three methods:

  1. Use $
Duncan$prestige
  1. Use [ ] and Specify the column name
Duncan[, "prestige"]
  1. Use attach() to access all columns by names
attach(Duncan)
prestige

If you use the 3rd method to attach dataset Duncan, you can use detach(Duncan) at the end when you are done with it.


For the mean() function and lm() function we used in chapter 1, we can all access the columns without using attach() function. See following examples:

  1. with attach()
attach(Duncan)

# mean of prestige
mean(prestige)
# linear regression of prestige on income and education
lm(prestige ~ income + education)

detach(Duncan)
  1. without attach()
# mean of prestige
mean(Duncan$prestige)
# linear regression of prestige on income and education
lm(prestige ~ income + education, data = Duncan)


2.2.3 Missing Values

Use the built-in dataset Freedman in car package. If we meet missing values in the dataset, how do we proceed the arithmetic without considering them in the data? We use na.rm to specify this request.

data(Freedman, package = "car")
head(Freedman$density, 20)  # first 20 values

mean(Freedman$density)
mean(Freedman$density, na.rm = TRUE)  # na.rm means NA-remove

2.2.4 Numeric Variables and Factors

If we construct R data frames by reading data from text files using read.table or from numeric and character vectors using data.frame, then our data frames will consist of two kinds of data: numeric variables and factors. Both read.table and data.frame by default translate character data and logical data into factors.

A factor is a representation of a categorical variable. Factors are stored more economically than chracter vectors, and they are stored saves information about the levels (category set) of a factor. When a factor is printed, its values are not quoted, as are the values of a character vector, and the levels of the factor are listed.

Use the built-in dataset Guyer in car package here. We can always check each variables mode anytime:

data(Guyer, package = "car")
head(Guyer)  # first 20 values
>   cooperation condition sex
> 1          49         P   M
> 2          64         P   M
> 3          37         P   M
> 4          52         P   M
> 5          68         P   M
> 6          54         P   F

> Levels: A P
is.character(Guyer$condition)

Guyer$perc.coop <- 100 * Guyer$cooperation/120

Guyer$cooperation <- with(Guyer, log(perc.coop/(100 - perc.coop)))

3. transform() - Create and Modify several variables at once

Data <- transform(Data, c = -c, asq = a^2, a.over.b = a/b)


4. Create factors from numeric data to categorical data

To divide the range of perc.coop into four equal-width bins, We have three methods to do this:

Guyer$coop.groups <- with(Guyer, cut(perc.coop, quantile(perc.coop, c(0, 1/3, 
    2/3, 1)), include.lowest = TRUE, labels = c("low", "med", "high")))

2.3.3 Lists

Lists are data structures composed of potentially heterogeneous elements. The elements of a list may be complex data structures, including other lists. Because a list can contain other lists as elements, each of which can also contain lists, lists are recursive structures.

list.1 <- list(mat.1 = A, mat.2 = B, vec = v)  # a 3-item list
list.1
> $mat.1
>      [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4]
> [1,]    1    4    7   10
> [2,]    2    5    8   11
> [3,]    3    6    9   12
> 
> $mat.2
>      [,1] [,2] [,3]
> [1,] "a"  "b"  "c" 
> [2,] "a"  "b"  "c" 
> [3,] "a"  "b"  "c" 
> [4,] "a"  "b"  "c" 
> 
> $vec
>  [1] 33 32 22 30 13 28 39 41 37  6

This list contains a numeric matrix, a character matrix, and a numeric vector.


2.3.4 Indexing


1. Indexing Vectors

A vector can be indexed by a single number or by a vector of numbers.

v
>  [1] 33 32 22 30 13 28 39 41 37  6
v[2]
> [1] 32
v[c(4, 2, 6)]
> [1] 30 32 28
v[c(4, 2, 4)]
> [1] 30 32 30


Negative indices suppresses the corresponding elements of the vector.

v[-c(2, 4, 6, 8, 10)]
> [1] 33 22 13 39 37


If a vector has a names attribute, then we can also index the elements by their names.

names(v) <- letters[1:10]
v
>  a  b  c  d  e  f  g  h  i  j 
> 33 32 22 30 13 28 39 41 37  6
v[c("f", "i", "g")]
>  f  i  g 
> 28 37 39


A vector can be indexed by a logical vector.

v < 6
>     a     b     c     d     e     f     g     h     i     j 
> FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE
v[v < 6]
> named integer(0)
# make a copy of v
vv <- v
vv[c(1, 3, 5)] <- 1:3
vv
>  a  b  c  d  e  f  g  h  i  j 
>  1 32  2 30  3 28 39 41 37  6
vv[c("b", "d", "f", "h", "j")] <- NA
vv
>  a  b  c  d  e  f  g  h  i  j 
>  1 NA  2 NA  3 NA 39 NA 37 NA


2. Indexing Matrices and Arrays

Indexing extends to matrices and to arrays. Indices corresponding to the different dimensions of an array are separated by commas.

A
>      [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4]
> [1,]    1    4    7   10
> [2,]    2    5    8   11
> [3,]    3    6    9   12
A[2, 3]
> [1] 8
A[c(1, 2), 2]  # rows 1 and 2, column 2
> [1] 4 5
A[c(1, 2), c(2, 3)]  # rows 1 and 2, columns 2 and 3
>      [,1] [,2]
> [1,]    4    7
> [2,]    5    8
A[c(1, 2), ]  # rows 1 and 2, all columns
>      [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4]
> [1,]    1    4    7   10
> [2,]    2    5    8   11


If we select elements in a single row or single column of a matrix, then R will automatically result in a vector but not a matrix with single row or column. Use drop = FALSE to fix this problem.

A[, 1]
> [1] 1 2 3
A[, 1, drop = FALSE]
>      [,1]
> [1,]    1
> [2,]    2
> [3,]    3


Negative indices will remove the specified rows or columns. You can still use logical vector to be your indices.

A[, -c(1, 3)]  # omit columns 1 and 3
>      [,1] [,2]
> [1,]    4   10
> [2,]    5   11
> [3,]    6   12
A[-1, -2]  # omit row 1 and column 2
>      [,1] [,2] [,3]
> [1,]    2    8   11
> [2,]    3    9   12
rownames(A) <- c("one", "two", "three")  # set row names
colnames(A) <- c("w", "x", "y", "z")  # set column names
A
>       w x y  z
> one   1 4 7 10
> two   2 5 8 11
> three 3 6 9 12
A[c("one", "two"), c("x", "y")]
>     x y
> one 4 7
> two 5 8
A[c(TRUE, FALSE, TRUE), ]
>       w x y  z
> one   1 4 7 10
> three 3 6 9 12


3. Indexing Lists

Similar as indexing vectors.

list.1
> $mat.1
>      [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4]
> [1,]    1    4    7   10
> [2,]    2    5    8   11
> [3,]    3    6    9   12
> 
> $mat.2
>      [,1] [,2] [,3]
> [1,] "a"  "b"  "c" 
> [2,] "a"  "b"  "c" 
> [3,] "a"  "b"  "c" 
> [4,] "a"  "b"  "c" 
> 
> $vec
>  [1] 33 32 22 30 13 28 39 41 37  6
list.1[c(2, 3)]  # elements 2 and 3
> $mat.2
>      [,1] [,2] [,3]
> [1,] "a"  "b"  "c" 
> [2,] "a"  "b"  "c" 
> [3,] "a"  "b"  "c" 
> [4,] "a"  "b"  "c" 
> 
> $vec
>  [1] 33 32 22 30 13 28 39 41 37  6
list.1[2]  # return a one-element list
> $mat.2
>      [,1] [,2] [,3]
> [1,] "a"  "b"  "c" 
> [2,] "a"  "b"  "c" 
> [3,] "a"  "b"  "c" 
> [4,] "a"  "b"  "c"
list.1[[2]]  # return a matrix
>      [,1] [,2] [,3]
> [1,] "a"  "b"  "c" 
> [2,] "a"  "b"  "c" 
> [3,] "a"  "b"  "c" 
> [4,] "a"  "b"  "c"


Double-bracket [[]] extracts a single-element list

# produces a one-element list
list.1["mat.1"]
> $mat.1
>      [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4]
> [1,]    1    4    7   10
> [2,]    2    5    8   11
> [3,]    3    6    9   12
# extracts a single element
list.1[["mat.1"]]
>      [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4]
> [1,]    1    4    7   10
> [2,]    2    5    8   11
> [3,]    3    6    9   12


You can also extract elements by $.

list.1$mat.1
>      [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4]
> [1,]    1    4    7   10
> [2,]    2    5    8   11
> [3,]    3    6    9   12


You can replace list elements, define new elements, delete an element:

# replace element
list.1$mat.1 <- matrix(1, 2, 2)
# new element
list.1$title <- "an arbitrary list"
# delete element
list.1$mat.2 <- NULL

list.1
> $mat.1
>      [,1] [,2]
> [1,]    1    1
> [2,]    1    1
> 
> $vec
>  [1] 33 32 22 30 13 28 39 41 37  6
> 
> $title
> [1] "an arbitrary list"
